{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TV5qA6ZNWHcAg6wszBJueq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The error is:\n```resources/js/lib/puck-config.tsx(28,38): error TS2503: Cannot find namespace 'JSX'.\nresources/js/lib/puck-config.tsx(29,13): error TS2604: JSX element type 'Tag' does not have any construct or call signatures.\nresources/js/lib/puck-config.tsx(29,13): error TS2786: 'Tag' cannot be used as a JSX component.\n  Its type 'string | number | symbol' is not a valid JSX element type.    Type 'number' is not assignable to type 'ElementType'.\n\n\n```\n\nThe issue is that in React 19 with the new JSX runtime, the `JSX` namespace isn't automatically available—I need to reference it as `React.JSX.IntrinsicElements` instead of just `JSX.IntrinsicElements` when casting the dynamic tag name.\n\n```\n\nts\nconst Tag = `h${Level}` as unknown as React.ElementType;\n```\n\nThis casts the template literal to React.ElementType so TypeScript knows it's a valid component. I need to import React to access React.ElementType, and then I can apply the same fix to the DataListBlock render type issue.\n\nThe problem with DataListBlock is that Puck expects the render function to return `Element` specifically, not the broader `ReactNode` type which includes `undefined`. I need to ensure DataListBlock returns `JSX.Element` instead.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":757,"cache_read_input_tokens":153405,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":757},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"13906b18-daff-4720-b7d8-a93a2992ee49","uuid":"4534de27-2c3f-4c83-acc0-2e9ffae9c3fc"}
