{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016aRKh1Z9iwJtF1Vew6g148","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The error at line 122 is: `Property 'status' does not exist on type '{}'`. The `flash` from `usePage<SharedData>().props` would be typed based on the index signature. Since `SharedData` has `[key: string]: unknown`, the `flash` destructuring would give `unknown` type. But the error says `{}` not `unknown`...Actually, looking at it more carefully - when you destructure from a type with an index signature, TypeScript might give the type as `unknown`. When doing `(unknown as {}).status`, TypeScript might not error on the access, but the result would be `unknown`.\n \nI'm realizing the error message says `type '{}'` which suggests TypeScript is inferring an empty object type rather than `unknown`. Optional chaining on `unknown` should work in modern TypeScript, so the issue might be that when destructuring `flash` from the index signature, it's being inferred as `{}` instead of `unknown`, which would explain why accessing `.status` fails. The real issue is that TypeScript resolves `flash` as `{}` when the property isn't explicitly defined on the type, even though the index signature should give `unknown`. The straightforward fix is to cast `flash` to the proper type with the optional properties and null/undefined handling, which lets TypeScript properly type the chained access.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":247,"cache_read_input_tokens":160824,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":247},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"13906b18-daff-4720-b7d8-a93a2992ee49","uuid":"7732865a-5545-40df-b876-00c3388319f1"}
